data.name: Times change but one can't help get a bit nostalgic on this day. I love college football, The U and truly miss the OB. Remember when the National Championship was decided on Jan 1st and often here in our own backyard? Nothing rocked like that place. It literally shook and anyone who ever stepped foot inside can attest to that fact. Miss her, the insane crowds, the 'hood, the cat kabob carts, ten dolla no blockee parking, the nasty leaky bathrooms, the Scorpions blaring... and most of all our Canes whuppin' ass while both opposing teams and their fans were intimidated coming into our house... and the OB was OUR house. 'Nuff said.

data.message: Thought about that place while watching Chris Fowler emote the other day. Walked in to cover a game next to him once. "I hate this fucking shithole!" said he...or something to that effect. I thought it had so much character and history though, despite being a massive dump. And housing loads of Rough Classless Assholes. They should have fixed it up.

Totally. Funny Fowler said that. It was like your fave hole in the wall pub. It was a dump, but it was our dump and a ridic home field advantage for both Fins and Canes. So much history, so many events from Superbowls to World Championship boxing matches, not to mention many concerts, too. They def should've saved her, man. Totally.
Great analogy. Exactly what it was. A dive stadium. Well at least they hooked up two Proper Scumbags with some shiny new shit there...
And Fowler is a Smug Northeast Blue Blood. Probably loves it in Bristol.

I literally grew up here. When they tore this down they tore down parts of my childhood and so much of so many other people's lives. From seeing Michael Jackson to all the Fins and Canes games... I don't even have to mention it, if you know, you know. Just seeing this picture brought a bittersweet smile to my face and an ocean of memories back.

Saw numerous shows there though my personal highlight will forever be '88 Monsters of Rock tour w Van Halen (headlining) plus Metallica, Scorpions and Kingdom Come! Lol Ridi!

Abel is so right.  It was our dump.  I would give anything for those uncomfortable but delightfully noisy aluminum bench seats right now.  But I realize that stadiums cannot last forever.  JFK Stadium in Philly, Memorial in Baltimore...these are a few of the places that stood and served admirably for a very long time, and we have some wonderful memories.  BUT...The Stadium Formerly Known As Joe Robbie is only 25 years old.  I can't help but notice that the lifespan of stadia seems to be shrinking.  There is not really a damn thing wrong with JRS except that the faded seats need to be upgraded.  We DO NOT need a dome for football.  Fix it up and let's see how many memories we can squeeze into the place in the next 25 years or so.
